QID161_TEXT:
This may be a matter of personal preference, or even cultural difference, but I find statements like "smart people get this" and "you must make sacrifices to gain success" to be rather condescending and obnoxious. For persuasion and encouragement, I prefer factual statements about possible gains - not stock lines that insinuate that I may not be working right or hard enough, or that I'm stupid for not agreeing with some method or statement. Frankly, lines like these sound like the justifications of someone who is unhappy about having spent all of their life doing nothing but work that they don't even enjoy, but can't admit it. 

The lines specifically about studying computer science were fine.

QID161_TEXT: Persuasive writing in this sense does not work when the statements come across as belittling to those who may think that they do not have the time/intelligence to do a degree. Degrees are inaccessible to some people and many can do just as well in life without one. There are many more options in the modern world and being "smart" in an academic sense is definitely not the most desirable trait anymore. Some of the statements annoyed me to read, as they felt insulting. Education is incredibly important at earlier stages in life, but some people may not be suited to further education at all. Making them feel bad for not wanting to do a degree or telling them that they "didn't work hard enough" is very wrong. People who do degrees and go in to highly specified work, will always earn less money than entrepreneurs who drop out of school and get a lucky break, the world isn't always fair. Money shouldn't be a reason that someone does a job, and trying to convince someone to study a specific subject should not involve monetary incentives, it should be about passion for the subject.

QID161_TEXT:
For someone like myself, I'm not motivated by money or security. I'm motivated by pursuing a life I would like to live. Obviously that requires having money, but it's a shallow motivational tool for me. To me, it's far more motivating to accentuate the qualities that are desirable in the kind of person who might achieve their goals. The destination isn't what I'm interested in I suppose, it's the journey, and to talk about goals doesn't interest me. Because once I achieve that goal, then what? I'll be stuck looking for another goal. The goal should be to live everyday in the best way possible.

I dunno, I'm probably rambling, and this might be useful to you. But I just know that telling me I could earn more money if I sacrifice however many years of my life isn't what's going to get me interested. Something along the lines of how much I will learn and grow as a person, which in turn affords new opportunities. It's the same line of reasoning, but it's a difference in priorities I suppose.

QID161_TEXT:
Cite the researches if he mentions particular statistics possibly. I believe any intelligent person nowadays knows not to trust "statistics / research shows" comments. We're in a society where numbers are fudged everyday and even academic research credibility can be placed into question. A strong statement saying "this is what it is" and not allowing the viewer to do their own research is about as bad as any American media. Although I guess it'd also dependent on the average intelligence of the user.

For the survey itself, I found it was difficult taking the topic out of context. As someone who has gone through the education system itself in Canada and witnesses my peers, colleagues and their career paths. I have observed just how little merit most of the statements hold. So my evaluations were based strictly on the format of the language rather than the topic itself. If it were to factor in the topics themselves I'd likely give them all 2 ranks less. (I know educated and educated individuals that do well and my brother has a masters in computing science)

QID161_TEXT:
The scale missed out number 5 and went straight from 4 to 6. Which was confusing when one of the attention checks said slide to 5. 

I thought the computer science information in particular "just about anyone can do it" and talking about how it's one of the highest paying jobs at the moment was really convincing and motivating and if I had heard that at a younger age I would have probably considered going down the computer science path.

I didn't like any of the stuff claiming simply getting a degree will get you a better job as I've experienced and seen time and time again it's very untrue. That type of talk did not convince me when I was younger, I went to university to give myself extra time to think before going into full time work, I never believed simply getting a degree would get me a better job and saying that would have never convinced me, even less so now when I know first hand it's not true. 

The statements saying about working hard will is a good use of time and will get you further in life etc. ( statements not mentioning college degrees ) was convincing and good.

QID161_TEXT: Statements like Galileo's don't sit right with me because they imply that everyone has access to the same information and resources. The idea that "smart people all know this" equates ignorance with stupidity. If your aim is to convince people to enter a field and to work hard at succeeding in it, there needs to be acknowledgment of obstacles. There need to be resources made available for folks who are struggling. Saying "anyone can do this with a little effort" will only yield benefits if you are willing to provide resources to maximize the effects of effort.

QID161_TEXT: When encouraging people, it's best not to compare them to other people or say that it is "simple," "common sense," "easy," etcetera. As people who are being convinced, we have likely not yet done those "simple" or "easy" things, which basically indirectly implies our incompetence to get with the program. Furthermore, forcing things also makes people feel as if they are losing autonomy, and most people would prefer to make their own choices, even if they're wrong, so focus on how things benefit the person, not society or whatnot. I would suggest going through Galileo's comments and editing any of their comments that may be patronizing or forceful, whether on accident or not.
